ve essays, it illustrates how human rights can be harnessed to generate democratic institutional innovations. Ultimately, this book brings the reader down from the heights of official human rights forums to the ground level of advocacy. It is a must-read for human rights advocates, development practitioners, students, educators, and all others interested in an equitable global society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHuman rights advocacyxCase studiesxAfrica. 0aHuman rights advocacyzAfricavCase studies. 0aHuman rightsxAfrica. 0aHuman rightszAfrica. 0aSocial rightsxAfrica. 0aSocial rightszAfrica. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh1 aPerelman, Jeremy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWhite, Lucie E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477643140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804776431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804776431.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles